 Farming-based Money flow 14 (1996) 93-102 
 
 Farm size, relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) and land-related policy in Cote d'Ivoire: 
 profit function analysis of rice farms 
 Akinwumi A. Adesina 
 
 a,*, 
 
 Kouakou K. Djato 
 
 b 
 
 - West Africa Rice Development Association, OJ BP 2551, Bouake, Cote d'lvoire 
 b Centre lvorien de Interestings Economiques et Sociales, Abidjan, Cote d'lvoire 
 Accepted 25 January 1996 
 
 Abstract 
 This paper examines the relative money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of small and large rice farms in Cote d'Ivoire using a profit function approach. No 
 differences in the relative money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of small and large farms were found. This end/end result is strong under different model 
 (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required). Land-related changes directed towards further concentration of landholding for large farms in Cote d'Ivoire cannot be reasonable 
 based on money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something). Results show that access to credit and use of modem rice varieties increase (a lot) (money made/good things received). To improve 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of rice farms, an fast program to provide information, credit, improved seeds and other inputs is needed. When 
 all the farms (i.e. large and small) are taken together, there is (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of allocative inefficiency. Plans are needed to remove such 
 management related inefficiencies in rice production either through the development of a better market price information system or effective 
 farmer-oriented technical training programs by rice extension workers. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 Farming-based policy makers in developing countries face hard decisions in their choice of land-related structure to (accomplish or gain with effort) the dual goals of growth and 
 equity in the farming-based part/area (Dorner, 1972; Khan 
 and Maki, 1979; Noronha, 1985; Lele and Clear jellywal, 
 1989; Deininger and Binswanger, 1995). Often, 
 land-related policies favor large farms under the thought (made beforehand) that they are more (money-based)/cheaply (producing a lot with very little waste) 
 than small farms (Dorner, 1972; Khan and Maki, 
 
 ' Corresponding author at: International Institute of (related to areas near the Equator/hot and humid) 
 Farming, Humid Forest Program, BP 2008, Yaounde, 
 Cameroon. 
 
 1979; Kydd and Christiansen, 1982; Lele and Clear jellywal, 1989; Kouadio and Pokou, 1991; Deininger and 
 Binswanger, 1995). A few attempts have been made 
 in Africa to encourage large scale farms. Examples 
 include policies favoring collectivized farming that 
 ruled production relations in Tanzania in the 
 1970s (McHenry, 1979); state-(forced (on people)/caused an inconvenient situation) (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) (changing from one form, state, or state of mind to another) arrangements in Kenya that led to further 
 land combining, concentration and (making something unimportant) of small farms (Brokensha and Glazier, 1973; 
 Njeru, 1978; Okoth-Ogendo, 1986); diversion of institutional credit to large farms in Kenya and Malawi 
 (Kydd and Christiansen, 1982; Lele and Meyers, 
 1986); subsidization of land settlement, crop-watering/rinsing with water 
 and mechanization costs in Nigeria (Lele et al., 
 1989); policy-caused land, labor and output market 
 
