 PI! SO 169-5150(96)0 1181-4 
 
 94 
 
 A.A. Adesina, K.K. Djato /Agricultural Money flow 14 ( 1996) 93-102 
 
 helping actions to favor large (related to Europe) farms over 
 African smallholder farms in Kenya, Zimbabwe and 
 South Africa (Deininger and Binswanger, 1995) or 
 (serving to severely limit or control) market (using different things) that gave large farms 
 legal rights to grow clearly stated/particular crops for export in 
 Malawi (Christiansen and Kydd, 1987). 
 The assumed superior money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 
 large farms may, however, be misleading due to the 
 high social costs of the special (and good) public policies 
 that have maintained them. Experiences with most 
 large-farm led land-related changes within dual farm size 
 structures have been mixed (Lele and Clear jellywal, 1989; 
 Collier et al., 1990; Bruce and Migot-Adholla, 1994). 
 Deininger and Binswanger (1995) suggest that incorporating rent looking (for) behavior in the explanation of production relations may explain the existence of such 
 dual farm size structures in Kenya, Zimbabwe and 
 South Africa. Policies that were used to reduce the 
 'reservation utility' of the African smallholder farms 
 in these countries included (serving to severely limit or control) land, labor and 
 output market rules. Without these 
 policy distortions, large (related to Europe) farms could not 
 have been competitive with the African smallholder 
 farms. Lele and Clear jellywal (1989) compared domestic 
 useful thing/valuable supply costs for the production of coffee and tea in 
 Kenya for large and smallholder farms. Their guesses showed a strong (serving to compare two or more things) advantage in 
 smallholder production, and they argued that this 
 possibly explains why the colonial government forced restrictions on smallholder farms producing 
 tea and coffee in Kenya. However, Lele and Clear jellywal 
 (1989) and Deininger and Binswanger (1995) and 
 did not specifically test for money-based (i.e. price and 
 technical) (wasting very little while working or producing something) differences between the large 
 and small farms in their intelligent analyses. 
 Previous studies in Asia have tested for relative 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) differences by farm size, with disagreeing 
 results. Lau and Yotopoulos (1971) and Yotopoulos 
 and Lau (1973) found that small wheat farms in the 
 Indian Punjab were more (money-based)/cheaply (producing a lot with very little waste) than 
 large farms. In Pakistan, Khan and Maki ( 1979) 
 found that large farms were more (money-based)/cheaply (producing a lot with very little waste) than small farms. However, these results are at 
 variance with those of Sidhu (1974) who found no 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of differences in the relative money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) or its parts/pieces of technical and pricing 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something), between small and large farms. The above 
 suggests the need to avoid (big statements based on very little information) on what is 
 
 clearly a complex issue. Because of major differences 
 in farming-based and institutional settings, (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) 
 from the previously-mentioned studies in Asia cannot be 
 used directly for informing land-related policy in Africa. 
 However, there is a low amount of studies in Africa that 
 test for relative money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) (Saleem, 1988) 
 by farm size in order to guide policy decision makers. Data limits have mostly prevented such 
 analysis, most especially in West Africa (Lele and 
 Clear jellywal, 1989). The goal of this paper is to test 
 for relative money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) differences between 
 small and large rice farms in Cote d 'Ivoire using the 
 profit function approach. The purpose of this paper 
 is different from that of Deininger and Binswanger 
 ( 1995), in that while they focused on creating 
 reasonable guesses for the existence of dual farm 
 size land-related structures, our aim is to decide/figure out 
 whether differences in money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) by farm 
 size exist in Cote d'Ivoire, the existence of dual farm 
 size land-related structure taken as given (Widner, 1993). 
 There is an on-going debate in Cote d'Ivoire on 
 the types of institutional changes needed to stimulate 
 rice production in the country (Cooperation Fran&#126;aise 
 de Developpement, 1993). With (lowering in number/getting worse) national 
 rice independence, Cote d'Ivoire has become the 
 second largest importer of rice in West Africa (average of 284200 t every year in 1988-1990) (West 
 Africa Rice Development Association, 1993). This 
 has again led some policy makers to argue in favor 
 of increasing domestic production through the encouragement of large farms. The argument for such 
 an approach is that it lowers extension and input 
 distribution costs, and secures/makes sure of easier and lower marketing costs with fewer producers. Although about 
 80% of rice farms in the country are smallholder 
 farms, the government has over the years encouraged 
 large farms through the importation and distribution 
 of highly helped pay for mechanized equipment, seed 
 and chemical inputs. For example, the government 
 established large, fully mechanized, and highly helped pay for upland rice farms in the northern part of the 
 country. The state has also given special (and good) tax 
 (permissions to not do something) for the import of large machinery 
 (Kouadio and Pokou, 1991). The lack of scientific 
 studies on the relative money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of large 
 and small farms in Cote d'Ivoire makes it hard 
 for policy makers in Cote d'Ivoire to test their 
 land-related policy for (accomplishing or gaining) growth and equity. 
 
