 2.2. Data 
 Data used to guess the model were collected 
 from August 1992 to April 1993 from a sample of 
 410 rice farms in villages in three districts of northem Cote d'Ivoire, namely Touba (67 farms), Korhogo (216 farms) and Katiola (127 farms). This 
 gave/given us with disaggregated micro-level data 2 - 
 The definition of farm size has been (number or thing that changes) in the 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) books, as what is carefully thought about/believed 'large' or 
 'small' is relative depending on the farming-based system settings. In Pakistan farming, Khan and Maki 
 ( 1979) classified large farms as those having 12.5 
 areas of land or over (i.e. 5 ha). Using Indian data, Yotopoulos and Lau (1973) and Sidhu (1974) classified 
 'large' farms as those with at least 10 areas of land (i.e. 4 
 ha). In this study, large farms were defined as farms 
 that have at least 5 ha. In their study in northern Cote 
 d'Ivoire, Kouadio and Pokou (1991) noted that average farm size of the large farms ranged from 5 to 28 
 ha, with a mean of 10 ha. To decide/figure out the strength of ends/end results from the first analysis, we will 
 also examine the effects of re-defining the dividing line 
 for large farms to 10 ha. Sensitivity of the ends/end results to alternate definitions of the dividing line, although very important given the potential (affecting lots of things in many ways for a long time) effects/results/suggestions of the results of farm (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 tests, is rarely tested (Khan and Maki, 1979). 
 
 2 The use of data from the districts also improved (quality of changing over time or at different places) in 
 the price data. We find the well-said argument of Sevilla-Siero 
 (1991) (p. 125) highly (connected/related) here: "[A]s soon as we bring into 
 the analysis (related to space or existing in space) (things to carefully think about) (and farming in most developing countries is par excellence a (related to where mountains, rivers, cities, etc., are located) broke up activity) we see locational differences in fanngate prices ....Thus depending on their location, farms will argue with different groups of output and input prices. Surprisingly, it is the wide 
 (land-area-based/location) breaking up/spreading out (typical and expected) of developing country farming (and the (land-area-based/location) price variablity caused by it) that 
 makes/gives (able to be done) the guess of (money made/good thing received) functions (in there/within that)". 
 
 3. Scientific results 
 
 3.1. Guess testing 
 The guessed results of the profit function and 
 factor share equations for the (wasting very little while working or producing something) tests are 
 given in Table 1. The limit/guideline guesses all have 
 the expected signs. The input prices all have the 
 possibly expected negative signs pointing to/showing that 
 the guessed profit function is curving out in input prices. 
 The coefficient on capital input is positive as expected, which agrees with the finding of Khan and 
 Maki (1979). In the model of Yotopoulos and Lau 
 (1973), the coefficient on the capital (number or thing that changes) was 
 found to be negatively signed due to what the authors described as mis-(detailed description of exactly what is required) of this (number or thing that changes). 
 Although extension (EXT) and education (EDUC) 
 positively influence (makes money/gets something good), their effects are not significant. However, access to credit (CRDT) and use 
 of modem varieties ( MV) are positively related to 
 (money made/good things received) and are usually significant. 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) has three parts/pieces: technical, allocative and money-based. Technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) can be 
 defined as the ability to (accomplish or gain with effort) a higher level of 
 output, given a almost the same  level of production inputs. 
 Allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) defines the extent to which 
 farmers make (producing a lot with very little waste) decisions by using inputs up 
 to the level at which their not important (thing that's given/work that's done) to 
 output value is equal to the factor cost. Money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) combines technical and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). Technical and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) are necessary, and when they happen together are (good) enough 
 conditions for (accomplishing or gaining) money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something). In order to deal with the/to speak to the  questions of relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 discussed above, we carried out the following (related to studying numbers) tests: 
 H1: small and large rice farms have equal relative 
 money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something); 
 H2: there is equal relative price (wasting very little while working or producing something) with 
 respect to labor and (material that makes plants grow better) for small and large 
 rice farms; 
 H3: there is equal relative technical and price 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) for small and large rice farms; 
 H4: if either H1 or H2 is rejected, H4 tests for 
 total price (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the large farms; 
 H5: if either H1 or H2 is rejected, H5 tests for 
 total price (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the small farms; 
 
 A.A. Adesina, K.K. Djato /Agricultural Money flow 14 ( 1996) 93-102 
 
 H6: maintaining the guess of equal relative 
 price (wasting very little while working or producing something), this guess tests for the total price (wasting very little while working or producing something) of both large and small farms 
 (i.e. as a group); 
 H7: this guess tests for constant returns to 
 scale in all factors of production. 
 We tested the (connected/related) guesses under the two 
 different (detailed description of exactly what is required) of the farm size dividing line. 
 Hl-H5 were tested from the (having no limits, rules, or barriers) model, 
 
