 and large rice farms in Cote d'lvoire. 
 
 3.2. Ability to stretch guesses and effects/results/suggestions 
 An issue of central interest to policy makers is the 
 (quality of quickly responding to things) of output supply and factor demands 
 to price policy, and how they are affected by investment and land policies (Lau and Yotopoulos, I979). 
 Such guesses are missing for rice in Cote d'Ivoire. 
 An advantage of the profit function approach is that 
 it permits plain/honest/easy derivation of own-price 
 and cross-price output supply and input demand 
 elasticities. Indirect guesses of production elasticities were came/coming from identities which link the 
 coefficients of the profit function and those of the 
 production function. It has been noted that these 
 indirect input elasticities, when compared with those 
 received/got from the production function, have the clear/separate advantage of (related to studying numbers) (state of always working or appearing the same way) (Sidhu, 
 197 4). These guesses of indirect elasticities are 
 compared with direct ability to stretch guesses received/got 
 from an guessed production function. All elasticities have the expected signs. The ability to stretch of rice 
 output is highest for labor (0.408) followed by (material that makes plants grow better) (0.267), land (0.204) and capital (0.036). 
