 4. Ends/end results 
 In this paper we examined the relative money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) of small and large rice farms in Cote 
 
 d'Ivoire using a profit function approach. We found 
 no difference in the money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of small 
 and large farms. This end/end result is strong under 
 different model (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required). Some land-related policy effects/results/suggestions for the rice part/area of Cote 
 d'Ivoire can be drawn from the findings. The most 
 (enough to be meaningful) is that land-related changes directed towards 
 further concentration of landholding for large farms 
 cannot be reasonable based on money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 Such programs can only be reasonable from the point of view of politics-based things to think about that often favor 
 the snob/snobby social class that control much of the large 
 scale farms in Cote d'Ivoire (Widner, 1993). At 
 times, the government has taken steps to mechanize 
 rice production through direct land taking and 
 re-distribution to form large scale farms. However, 
 money-based studies of large-scale fully mechanized 
 rice projects in northern Cote d'lvoire (i.e. Grand 
 Travaux, Projet Soja) show very high money-based 
 losses (Berger et al., 1990). The preference for a 
 large-farm led approach to rice production is a bias 
 not supported by any (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of superior money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) of large farms. 
 Secondly, results show that within the (related to the existence of two things) 
 farm size land-related structure in Cote d'Ivoire, there 
 exists (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of total allocative inefficiency. 
 Policy helping actions are needed to remove such management related inefficiencies in rice production either through the development of a better market 
 price information system or effective farmer-oriented 
 technical training programs by rice extension workers. 
 Finally, results point to/show that access to credit and 
 use of modem rice varieties increase (a lot) 
 (money made/good things received). A few improved rice varieties are available 
 in Cote d'lvoire, but many farms do not have access 
 to them because of poor seed distribution service, 
 and ineffectiveness of the extension service. To improve technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of rice farms, a more 
 fast program to provide information, credit, 
 improved seeds and other inputs is needed. The 
 recent establishment of a combined (away from cities) development (service business/government unit/power/functioning) (ONADER: Organization Nationale 
 d' Appui au_pair Developpement (away from cities) e) will be useful in providing farmers access to these inputs. 
 Our results strongly suggest that government policies 
 on such farm support services should not be (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) 
 against smallholder rice farms. 
 
